Packet Filtering and Analysis using Wireshark/Burp Suite
1.Open VirtualBox → Kali VM → Settings → Network.
2.Set Adapter 1:
▪ Attached to: Bridged Adapter
▪ Promiscuous Mode: Allow All
▪ Cable Connected: ✔️
3.Start Kali Linux VM
4.open terminal
5.sudo wireshark
6.Select network interface eth0
7. Apply Display Filters for Analysis (opntional->dns,tls,i.addr==18.161.216.37)


///////////////////////////////////////////
Part B: Capturing Login Credentials over HTTP
1.open terminal
2.sudo service apache2 start
sudo mkdir -p /var/www/html/testlogin
cd /var/www/html/testlogin
3.create login html page
4.sudo nano login.html

html
CopyEdit
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<title>Test Login Page</title>
</head>
<body>
<h2>Login Form</h2>
<form action="login.php" method="post">
Username: <input type="text" name="username"><br><br>
Password: <input type="password" name="password"><br><br>
<input type="submit" value="Login">
</form>
</body>
</html>
Save (Ctrl + O → Enter → Ctrl + X).

5.create pho file
sudo nano login.php
php
CopyEdit
<?php
$username = $_POST['username'];
$password = $_POST['password'];
echo "<h2>Login Attempt</h2>";
echo "Username: " . $username . "<br>";
echo "Password: " . $password . "<br>";
?>

6.sudo service apache2 status
sudo service apache2 start

7.Browser:
http://127.0.0.1/testlogin/login.html

8.Open Wireshark → select lo (loopback) interface.
9.Start capture.
10.• Apply filter:
http.request.method == "POST"
 or right click on post
11.Step 7 – Perform Login Attempt
• Username: admin
• Password: test123
• Submit form.
12.Step 8 – Analyze Packets
• Locate POST packet.
• Right-click → Follow → TCP Stream.
• Credentials will be visible in plain text.










